&lt;p&gt;Coming soon are is a more updated BoM, CAD renderings (and possibly files), and more.
So &lt;a href=&#34;/index.xml&#34;&gt;stay tuned&lt;/a&gt; so you&amp;rsquo;ll get to see this stuff.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2 id=&#34;concept&#34;&gt;Concept&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The concept for the &lt;em&gt;CaaB&lt;/em&gt; is sort of like a Boom Box:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;
&lt;img alt=&#34;Boom Box (image credit: Sorin Mares)&#34;
class=&#34;js-img&#34;
data-src=&#34;/post/caab-the-concept/images/boombox.png&#34;
src=&#34;/post/caab-the-concept/images/boombox_hu8437552645e4ba1d5674dcf64bda3015_1719739_0x400_resize_box_2.png&#34;&gt;
&lt;/img&gt;
&lt;figcaption&gt;Boom Box (image credit: Sorin Mares)&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The boom box is powerful and portable, and so is the &lt;em&gt;CaaB&lt;/em&gt;, it packs a punch for it&amp;rsquo;s size, and it&amp;rsquo;s fully portable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;design&#34;&gt;Design&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The design of the &lt;em&gt;CaaB&lt;/em&gt; is to be similar in that of a boom box, a wide rectangular box with a handle on top. It would fit a router, four ODroid HC1s, a PSU, some cables, and some special OLED Display toys (I&amp;rsquo;ll cover what those are in &lt;a href=&#34;#hardware&#34;&gt;hardware&lt;/a&gt;). One of the sides would swing open to reveal the innards of the device, while the other would have USB, my OLED displays and other ports plus a switch or two.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;figure&gt;
&lt;img alt=&#34;Drawing of the inside view of the CaaB (image copyright: Mendel Greenberg)&#34;
class=&#34;js-img&#34;
data-src=&#34;/post/caab-the-concept/images/front_inside.png&#34;
src=&#34;/post/caab-the-concept/images/front_inside_hu72bb49716f0d001dfcba4aa9c1d1c056_398168_0x400_resize_box_2.png&#34;&gt;
&lt;/img&gt;
&lt;figcaption&gt;Drawing of the inside view of the CaaB (image copyright: Mendel Greenberg)&lt;/figcaption&gt;
&lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;hardware&#34;&gt;Hardware&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The hardware required would be:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;4 ODroid HC1s&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;4 &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.amazon.com/dp/B076JDVRLP&#34;&gt;Cool OLED Things&lt;/a&gt; (if dead &lt;a href=&#34;http://archive.ph/ZYA8A&#34;&gt;click here&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1 280W PSU&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1 Router&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A collection of some different kinds of cables&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;A sheet of metal (to cut)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;h2 id=&#34;conclusion&#34;&gt;Conclusion&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s the idea, I&amp;rsquo;ll be back soon with more precise details in another article, and watch this page for updates, because it will be updated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Over the next little while I will be taking you on a journey as I set up my own little, private, portable, and cool ARM server cluster.
As is indicated by the title, this project will called the &amp;ldquo;Cluster as a Box&amp;rdquo; or CaaB.
This is &lt;strong&gt;not a how-to guide&lt;/strong&gt;, this is me documenting my experience in a format that you may find informative (and hopefully you&amp;rsquo;ll learn something).
This will also act as a nice way to test my &lt;a href=&#34;/project&#34;&gt;Project&lt;/a&gt; format, so we&amp;rsquo;ll see how it goes!&lt;/p&gt;
